'''Bryan James Gunn''' (born 22 December 1963 in [[Thurso]]) is a Scottish former professional [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] and [[manager (association football)|football manager]]. After learning his trade with [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] in the early 1980s, he spent most of his playing career at [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], the club with which he came to be most closely associated. This was followed by a brief spell back in Scotland with [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] before his retirement as a player in 1998.

Gunn feels the peak of his playing career was making what he calls the [[Glossary of association football terms#Save|save]] of his life in [[Bayern Munich v Norwich City|the UEFA Cup match against Bayern Munich]] in 1993. This event was called the summit of Norwich City's history by ''[[The Independent]]''. He is one of only nine Norwich players to win the club's [[Norwich City F.C. Player of the Year|Player of the Year]] award twice. He was made an inaugural member of [[Norwich City F.C. Hall of Fame|Norwich City's Hall of Fame]]. He was a member of the [[Scotland national football team]], making six appearances for his country in the early 1990s.

Gunn worked for years behind the scenes at Norwich in a variety of roles, from matchday hosting to coaching. He was appointed temporary manager towards the end of the [[2008-09 Football League Championship|2008<U+2013>09 season]] and then confirmed as permanent manager during the summer. However,  after a 7<U+2013>1 home defeat in the opening game to local rivals [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]], he lost his job a week into the [[2009<U+2013>10 Football League One]] season.

Since the death of his young daughter from [[leukaemia]] in 1992, Gunn has been extensively involved in fundraising to combat the disease and its effects. As of 2011 he has raised more than <U+00A3>1 million for research into childhood leukaemia. The money has been used to fund projects to improve the lives of children with leukaemia and their families, notably a national telephone support line. The city of [[Norwich]] recognised Gunn's charity work and his long association with the city's football club by naming him [[List of Shrievalties|Sheriff]] for 2002. Published in 2006, his autobiography, ''In Where it Hurts: My Autobiography'', includes a foreword by his former manager [[Alex Ferguson]].

==Early life==
Gunn was born on 22 December 1963 in [[Thurso]], Scotland,<ref name="awkward" /> "ten miles from [[John o' Groats|John o<U+2019>Groats]]"<!-- sic -->.<ref name="fixed">{{Cite news | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/article997906.ece | work = [[The Times]] | location = London | title = Gunn fixed on target | first = Rick| last = Broadbent | date = 19 January 2004|accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> His parents were James Gunn, a long-distance lorry driver, and Jessie Sinclair, a canteen worker at the [[Dounreay]] nuclear power plant; the pair had married despite being on opposite sides of a family feud stretching back to the 16th century.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=2}} James was an amateur sportsman, playing football on the right wing for local team [[Invergordon F.C.]] and winning medals at [[highland games]] events.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=5}}

The Gunn family home in Thurso was a farm,{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=3}} and the young Bryan would often pester the farmhands to play football with him. They would use a [[turnip]] if no ball was available.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=3}} By the age of four he was keen on goalkeeping; he was fearless of injury and enjoyed diving on the ball.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=3}} When Bryan was four-and-a-half, the family moved to [[Invergordon]], 20 miles from [[Inverness]].{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=3}} He attended Park Primary School in the town and joined the school football team.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=6}} Future professional [[Bobby Geddes]] was favoured over him as first-choice goalkeeper for the team;{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=6}} Gunn played as an [[Glossary of association football terms#O|outfield player]] until Geddes moved on to secondary school.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=7}}

Gunn attended secondary school at [[Invergordon Academy]] from 1975 to 1980,{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=8}} and gained [[O Level]]s in a variety of subjects, including English, maths, history and chemistry. He failed his French exam after taking it while "on the road" with [[Scotland national under-15 football team|Scotland under-15s]].{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=20}} At the age of 13, he was invited to play for the under-15 Invergordon F.C. team by one of his school teachers, who managed the team.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=9}} The team was beaten 9<U+2013>0 in Gunn's debut,{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=9}} but his subsequent performances attracted the attention of national selectors, and he joined the Scotland under-15 squad around the same time he signed for [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] at age 14.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rchs.uhi.ac.uk/RJ2000c/rj2000_12_dec/dec15/Reflections/index.html | publisher = [[University of the Highlands and Islands]]| title = Reflections| accessdate=15 March 2011 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110410031107/http://www.rchs.uhi.ac.uk/RJ2000c/rj2000_12_dec/dec15/Reflections/index.html|archivedate=10 April 2011}}</ref>

==Playing career==

===Aberdeen===
[[File:Alex Ferguson.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Alex Ferguson standing inside a stadium|The manager of Aberdeen, [[Alex Ferguson]], mentored Gunn.]]
Gunn commenced his professional career with Aberdeen in 1980,<ref name="Aberdeen">{{cite web | url = http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20080914/rmd-fps-interview_2260392_1393830 | publisher = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen F.C]] | title = RMD Fps interview| accessdate =8 March 2011}}</ref> and forged a good relationship with then-Aberdeen manager [[Alex Ferguson]]<U+2014>evidenced by the fact that in 1997 Ferguson brought [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] to [[Carrow Road]] for Gunn's [[testimonial match]].<ref name="fixed" /> While an apprentice at Aberdeen, Gunn was a frequent babysitter for Ferguson's children.<ref name="peppers">{{Cite news | url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2009/mar/23/birmingham-norwich-championship | work = [[The Guardian]] | location = London | accessdate =8 March 2011 | title = Gunn peppers Birmingham's automatic promotion hopes | first=Phil | last=Shaw|date = 23 March 2009}}</ref> He later said, "I probably babysat more than I played".<ref name="Aberdeen" /> Gunn portrays the relationship as warm, but businesslike:<ref name="fixed" />

{{quote|I'd stay over and we'd read the Sunday papers together. He was good to me. I was struggling for cash once and went in and told him I was going on holiday and was there any chance of an advance. He got on the phone and said: "Big Bryan Gunn's coming down to sign a new contract." It wasn't what I meant. I got my holiday money but he got another year out of me, too.}}

As a youngster, Gunn did not always play in goal and he was viewed as a handy outfield player in his early years at Aberdeen.<ref name="HoFs" /> Ferguson recalls, "He could strike a ball as well as anyone, so well in fact that I once played him at centre-forward in a reserve match ... He scored a brilliant goal ... It was a marvellous moment."{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|pp=xiii<U+2013>xiv}} However, as a professional, and at his adult height of {{convert|6|ft|2|in|m|abbr=on}},<ref name="soccerbase">{{cite web | url = http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=3143| title = Bryan Gunn| publisher =[[Soccerbase]]|accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref> Gunn settled into playing in goal.<ref name="HoFs" />

Gunn ascribes much of his goalkeeping success to the support of Belgian [[Marc de Clerck]], a specialist goalkeeping coach at Aberdeen. At a time when few British teams provided such training,<ref name="Aberdeen" /> de Clerck introduced Gunn and Scottish international keeper [[Jim Leighton]] to what were then innovative training techniques. The goalkeepers would participate in special drills whilst training with the rest of the squad.<ref name="Aberdeen" /> Gunn also notes the influence of Aberdeen coach [[Teddy Scott]], who taught the value of hard work and dedication;<ref name="Aberdeen" /> Gunn also served as a [[boot boy]] for [[Alex McLeish]].<ref name="peppers" /> Leighton's presence meant that Gunn played only 21 games for Aberdeen.<ref name="awkward">{{cite web | url = http://www.afc.co.uk/page/PlayerArchive/0,,10284,00.html | publisher= [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen F.C]] | accessdate =8 March 2011| title = Player archive | at= Reader must specify "Bryan Gunn" in Name field and select Update}}</ref> He made his debut against [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] at [[Pittodrie Stadium|Pittodrie]] on 30 October 1982,<ref name="HoFs" /> and went on to keep four [[clean sheets]] for the club.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20090401/afc-goalkeepers-_2212158_1631076| publisher = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen F.C]] | accessdate =23 March 2011|title = Aberdeen's Goalkeepers 1970<U+2013>2009 | date=1 April 2009}}</ref> Despite being rivals for a first-team place, Gunn had an excellent relationship with Leighton that included joining Leighton's family for a meal once a week.<ref name="Aberdeen" />

Gunn's training and performances for the reserve team and occasional first-team appearances paid dividends: he was called up for the [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland under-21 team]], and made his debut in November 1983 against [[East Germany national under-21 football team|East Germany]].<ref name="Aberdeen" />{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=54}} He also received [[Scottish League Cup]]{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=60}} and [[European Cup Winners Cup]]<ref name="ecwc" /> winner's medals while with Aberdeen, although he was an unused substitute in both finals. He made an unexpected appearance in the [[1985<U+2013>86 European Cup#Quarter-finals|1986 European Cup quarter final]], against [[IFK G<U+00F6>teborg|Gothenburg]]. "Jim and I were warming up and he lost [his] contact lenses [so] I ended up being included in the starting line up," Gunn recalls.<ref name="Aberdeen" /> Gunn had an excellent match: ''[[The Glasgow Herald]]'''s match report stated, "Only outstanding work by [[Willie Miller]] and Bryan Gunn kept the Swedes at bay".<ref name="Swede">{{Cite news | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=F7xAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w6UMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3785,1343778&dq=bryan+gunn&hl=en| title = European Nightmare for Aberdeen| page=22|first=Jim|last=Reynolds|date=6 March 1986|accessdate=29 March 2011|work=[[The Glasgow Herald]]|location=Glasgow}}</ref> As well as making several key saves, he was credited with playing a part in Aberdeen's second goal following a long kick upfield.<ref name="Swede" />

As Leighton was unlikely to be dislodged, Ferguson promised to find Gunn another club,<ref name="fixed" /> and fulfilled his pledge when he sold him for <U+00A3>100,000 to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in October 1986.<ref name="HoFs">{{cite web | url = http://www.aberdeensportscouncil.com/Gothenburg%20Hall%20of%20Fame%20Special.pdf | publisher = Aberdeen Sports Council | accessdate =8 March 2011|format=PDF | title = Hall of Fame special}}</ref> The transfer nearly went through in the summer of 1986, but Ferguson delayed the move until October to allow time for Leighton to recover from an injury.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=72}}

===Norwich City===
[[File:KenBrown.JPG|thumb|left|alt=Photo of Ken Brown| [[Ken Brown (footballer born 1934)|Ken Brown]], the Norwich manager who signed Bryan Gunn for the Norfolk club]]
Gunn says of the move south: "Norwich was easy to settle into, a bit like Aberdeen in many ways<U+2014>a city surrounded by lovely countryside and lots of farms."<ref name="square" /> However, since he joined the club partway into the new season, he initially found it difficult to take over as first-choice goalkeeper.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=72}} Gunn had been bought as a replacement for England international goalkeeper [[Chris Woods]], who had moved to [[Rangers F.C.]] Meanwhile, reserve team keeper [[Graham Benstead]] made a series of good performances and Norwich were top of the league.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=72}}<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.thediamondsfc.com/page/A-ZofDiamonds/0,,10784~1219414,00.html| publisher = [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds F.C]]| title = Graham Benstead| accessdate =22 March 2011|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110703030330/http://www.thediamondsfc.com/page/A-ZofDiamonds/0,,10784~1219414,00.html|archivedate=3 July 2011}}</ref> Ken Brown wanted to be fair to Benstead and made Gunn wait.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=72}} A 6<U+2013>2 defeat at [[Anfield]] proved to be the catalyst for Gunn's promotion to the first team.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=72}} He made his debut in a [[Full Members Cup]] win against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], conceding a penalty,{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=73}} and made his league debut in a 2<U+2013>1 victory against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] at Carrow Road on 8 November 1986.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|pp=74<U+2013>75}}

Norwich went on to finish [[1986-87 in English football#First Division|fifth in the First Division]] in his first season, their highest-ever league finish at the time.<ref name="square" /> By May 1988 Gunn's consistency meant his value had risen considerably, and the club reportedly declined a <U+00A3>500,000 offer from [[Ian Porterfield]] to take the goalkeeper back to Aberdeen.<ref name="500K">{{Cite news | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4TpAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=U1kMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3466,3814404&dq=bryan+gunn&hl=en| title = Porterfield fails to catch a keeper|work = [[The Glasgow Herald]]|location=Glasgow|page=40|date=13 May 1988| accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> The purpose of the proposed transfer was to replace Leighton, who by then had moved to Manchester United, where he was reunited with Alex Ferguson.<ref name="500K" />

Norwich reached the semi-final of the [[FA Cup]] in 1989 with Gunn in goal, but he missed the semi-final in 1992 through injury. What has been described as his<U+2014>and Norwich's<U+2014>greatest moment came in their [[Bayern Munich v Norwich City|upset victory]] over European giants [[Bayern Munich]] in the [[UEFA Cup]] in 1993. ''The Independent'' described the match as "the pinnacle of Norwich City's history".<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-5182545.html |title = Football: Canaries show they are back on song| first=Steve |last=Tongue |work= [[The Independent]]|location=London|date= 24 September 2002|accessdate=23 May 2011}}</ref> Gunn made several saves that kept the Canaries in the match. He describes the save he made from Bayern striker [[Adolfo Valencia]] as the finest of his career;<ref name="square2" /> it has also been described as "one of the most outstanding saves by a City goalkeeper".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/NewsDetails/0,,10355~407834,00.html| publisher = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City F.C]] | accessdate =11 May 2011 | title = Relive Bayern Munich in this exclusive weekend break |date = 17 November 2004}}{{dead link|date=February 2013}}</ref> However, he was involved in an [[own-goal]] incident in an [[East Anglian Derby]] match in the 1995<U+2013>96 season, when a backpass from [[Robert Ullathorne]] bounced awkwardly off the pitch and over Gunn's attempted clearance kick.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.greenun24.co.uk/ipswich-town/matthews_own_goal_creates_a_town_landmark_1_653520|work = The Green'Un| location=Suffolk|publisher = [[Archant]]| title = Matthews<U+2019> own goal creates a Town landmark | first=Elvin|last=King|date=21 September 2010|accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref>
{{Quote box
 | quote  = "The major highlights of my time at Norwich were the UEFA Cup run and qualifying for it. Norwich finished 3rd in the first ever Premier League season ... The match against Bayern Munich ... was a great occasion where I pulled off my best ever save ... In 1989 we finished 4th in Division 1 and got to the FA cup semi-final ... The main disappointment was being relegated in 1994/95 after I broke my leg [when] we were 7th in the Premier League ... I also ... let in a calamitous goal at [the] home of our arch rivals Ipswich Town. Robert Ullathorne's backpass bobbled (the pitch was crap) over my attempted kick and ended up in the back of the net. Very embarrassing."
 | source = Bryan Gunn, Squarefootball.com<ref name="square2" />
 | width  = 35%
 | align  = right
}}

In November 1989, Gunn was involved in a controversial incident that attracted significant media attention.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|pp=123<U+2013>125}} Norwich played [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at [[Highbury Stadium|Highbury]] and with five minutes remaining, Arsenal's [[David O'Leary]] scored an equaliser that brought the scores to 3<U+2013>3. Then, in the dying seconds of the match, the referee awarded Arsenal a [[penalty kick]]<U+2014>and the chance to seal the match. The Norwich players were already annoyed by the match situation, and their perception was that the decision was "really dodgy".{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|pp=123<U+2013>125}} Gunn saved [[Lee Dixon]]'s shot, but the ball was not cleared. In the resulting melee, [[Mark Bowen (footballer)|Mark Bowen]] and [[Ian Culverhouse]] for Norwich and [[Alan Smith (footballer born 1962)|Alan Smith]] for Arsenal challenged for the ball.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|pp=123<U+2013>125}} "The three of them got in an almighty tangle and the ball, along with all of them, was bundled over the line," Gunn remembers.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|pp=123<U+2013>125}} The goal was awarded, but the situation rapidly deteriorated: the three players in the goal had "a little skirmish". Separately, Arsenal's [[Nigel Winterburn]] gave "a gloat to [[Dale Gordon]], who promptly pushed him".{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|pp=123<U+2013>125}} The result was mayhem:
<blockquote>All of a sudden it was kicking off, big time. Everyone started piling in, right in front of me... The only people not involved were [Arsenal players] John Lukic, Tony Adams, David O'Leary and me... I went over to break things up... and spotted the cavalry coming over the half-way line, in the shape of O'Leary and Adams. I felt it was my job to head them off at the pass and moved in, instinctively grabbing Adams with one hand and thumping him with the other."{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|pp=123<U+2013>125}}</blockquote>

All but one of the 22 players on the pitch were involved in the fracas,<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.pinkun.com/home/it_can_be_reffing_hell_in_charge_of_canaries_1_644478| title = It can be reffing hell in charge of Canaries |first = David|last=Cuffley|accessdate =23 May 2011|date = 14 February 2009| location=Norfolk|publisher=[[Archant]]| work = The Pink 'Un}}</ref> but no one was sent off. The next day, the newspapers carried headlines and photos of what they called 'The Highbury Brawl'.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|pp=123<U+2013>125}} That afternoon, Gunn received a phone call from a ''[[Today (UK newspaper)|Today]]'' journalist, who told him that the Arsenal players had said Gunn had instigated the fight.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|pp=123<U+2013>125}} Enraged,{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|pp=123<U+2013>125}} the Norwich keeper retorted that it was the other way around. Monday's headline read "Gunn blames Arsenal".{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|pp=123<U+2013>125}} Gunn was censured by the [[Football Association]] and warned about his future conduct. Both clubs were fined, and Gunn was docked a fortnight's wages (about <U+00A3>800) by Norwich City.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|pp=123<U+2013>125}}

Under the management of [[Gary Megson]], Norwich were seventh in the Premier League in the 1994<U+2013>95 season<ref name="square2" /> when Gunn broke and dislocated his ankle whilst playing against [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]].<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-beleaguered-ipswich-pick-burley-1390876.html| work = [[The Independent]] | title = Football: Beleaguered Ipswich pick Burley| first = Andy|last=Martin|date=29 December 1994|accessdate=22 March 2011| location=London}}</ref> His importance to the team was underlined when they subsequently plummeted down the table, winning just one of their remaining 17 games as Gunn recovered.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.wsc.co.uk/content/view/3395/38/| work = [[When Saturday Comes]]| location=London| title = Nightmare for Norwich | date = 5 May 2009 | accessdate =22 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.football.co.uk/hull_city/megson-_no_favours_for_hull_rss104457.shtml| title = Megson: No favours for Hull| accessdate =22 March 2011|date = 15 May 2009 | publisher = [[Eurosport]]}}</ref> The team was ultimately relegated.<ref name="seasons" /> Gunn retained a regular first team place for the 1995-96 season and, beginning with the match against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]] on 17 February 1996, began to [[captain (association football)|captain]] the side, initially in the absence of regular captain [[Jon Newsome]] then on a permanent basis after Newsome left the club. However, when [[Mike Walker (Welsh footballer)|Mike Walker]] took over as manager for the following 1996-97 season, he appointed [[Ian Crook]] as captain instead.

Gunn's final first-team game for the club was a 1<U+2013>0 defeat at [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe]] on 31 January 1998.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=260}} According to the ''[[Sunday Mirror]]'', he produced "a sparkling display", which proved his abilities had "not been dulled by time".<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Fugle+bungle+a+gift+for+Gradi.-a060659366|accessdate=10 February 2013 |title = Fugle bungle a gift for Gradi| first= Ray|last=Clarkin| work= [[Sunday Mirror]] |location=London| date = 1 February 1998}}</ref> Gunn made 478 first team appearances for Norwich in all competitions.<ref name="soccerbase" /> He was voted [[Norwich City F.C. Player of the Year|Norwich City Player of the Year]] in 1988 and 1993.<ref name="poty">{{cite web | url = http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/History/0,,10355~1132064,00.html | title = Player of the Season 1967<U+2013>2010| publisher = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City F.C]]|accessdate=10 March 2011|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110423130728/http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/History/0,,10355~1132064,00.html|archivedate=23 April 2011}}</ref> The latter award came at the end of the [[1992<U+2013>93 FA Premier League|1992<U+2013>93 FA Premier League season]], in which Norwich finished third in the [[Premier League]], their best-ever performance.<ref name="seasons">{{cite web | url = http://stats.football365.com/cgi-bin/teamrecords.pl?team=Norwich_City| title = All-Time Records Historical results for Norwich City|publisher=football365.com| accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref> The club awarded Gunn a testimonial match in 1996, and Alex Ferguson brought Manchester United to Carrow Road.<ref name="fixed" />
{{clear}}

===Hibernian===
[[File:Marshall, Andy.jpg|right|thumb|alt=A photograph of Andy Marshall| [[Andy Marshall]] displaced Gunn from the Norwich first team.]]
In the 1997<U+2013>98 season, Gunn was forced out of the Norwich team by the emergence of [[Andy Marshall]].<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/3579435.stm | title = Marshall completes comeback | first = Lewis|last=Wiltshire|publisher=BBC Sport| accessdate =10 March 2011| date = 1 April 2004| quote = Marshall eventually dislodged Bryan Gunn from the first team at Carrow Road ... }}</ref> With his first-team opportunities at Norwich now limited, he signed a deal with Hibernian in February 1998, for a three-month loan.<ref name="hibs loan" /><ref>{{Cite news | url = http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/smgpubs/access/60151051.html?dids=60151051:60151051&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+17%2C+1998&author=&pub=The+Herald&desc=Gunn+returns+north+for+Hibs&pqatl=google | work = [[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] | location=Glasgow| accessdate =8 March 2011| date = 17 February 1998| title = Gunn returns north for Hibs}}</ref> According to Scottish transfer regulations the loan deal was invalid, so instead he was swiftly transferred on a permanent basis for an undiclosed fee, later revealed by Gunn to have been <U+00A3>25,000.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|pp=260<U+2013>261}}

Gunn's reflections on joining Hibernian are tinged with regret: "[leaving Norwich was] very difficult indeed. I had spent 12 great years at Norwich and suddenly I was not regarded as the number 1 (by Mike Walker) anymore."<ref name="square2" /> He joined Hibernian when they were bottom of the [[Scottish Premier Division]]; Alex McLeish had recently been appointed [[manager (association football)|manager]].<ref name="hibs loan">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/football-mcleish-seeks-belief-from-his-hibernian-side-1146095.html|title=Football: McLeish seeks belief from his Hibernian side|work=[[The Independent]]|date=21 February 1998|accessdate=9 March 2011|location=London}}</ref>

Gunn was unable to save the club from relegation to the [[Scottish Football League First Division|First Division]], but signed a two-year contract in July 1998.<ref name="highbeam">{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-17841939.html|last=Scott|first=Gordon|title=Gunn signs Hibs deal |work=[[Edinburgh Evening News]]|location=Edinburgh| date=7 July 1998|accessdate=1 June 2011}}</ref> However, a [[hairline fracture]] to his leg,<ref name="hairline">{{Cite news | url = http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-18687969.html| work = [[The Scotsman]] | accessdate=28 March 2011| title = Gunn forced to hang up gloves|first=Angus|last=Wright|date=31 March 1999|location=Edinburgh}}</ref> sustained during the 1998 [[close season]], effectively ended his playing career. On his doctors' advice, Gunn formally retired in March 1999.<ref name="hairline" />

Despite his mixed feelings on joining the club, Gunn's overall impression of his time in Edinburgh is upbeat: "I only played 12 games for the Hibees but it was great. We beat [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] in my only [[Edinburgh derby|derby]] game 2<U+2013>1 ([[John Robertson (footballer born 1964)|John Robertson]] scored his 50th goal for Hearts in derbies but I told him it was worth nothing as we had won){{#tag:ref| [[John Robertson (footballer born 1964)|John Robertson]] scored 27 goals in [[Edinburgh derby]] matches.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.londonhearts.com/scores/misc/eras.htm#sc1|publisher = London Hearts Supporters Club | accessdate = 26 May 2011 | title = Heart of Mid-Lothian vs Hibernians by Era}}</ref>|group="note"}} and had a clean sheet at [[Celtic Park]] (stopping them from winning the [[Scottish Premier Division|SPL]] that day)."<ref name="square2" /> He received what he described as a "wonderful reception" from Aberdeen fans when playing for Hibernian against his former club.<ref name="square2" />
{{Clear}}
