===Internationals===

Gunn represented [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] at the youth international level. He was part of the squad that won the 1982 [[UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship|UEFA European Under-18 Football Championship]]<!-- tournament has subsequently been renamed -->, but was unavailable to play in the final because Aberdeen had reached the [[1982 Scottish Cup Final]]. He was replaced by [[Robin Rae]] for the final, in which the Scots beat Czechoslovakia 3<U+2013>1.<ref name="u19 champion">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/article520082.ece|title=Caught in Time: Scotland are European youth champions, 1982|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=8 May 2005|last=White|first=Neil|accessdate=8 March 2011|location=London}}</ref>

In 1983, Gunn travelled with the [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland Under-19s]] to Mexico for the [[1983 FIFA World Youth Championship]].{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=49}} Gunn played in all four of Scotland's matches and it was a formative experience, as he faced a variety of challenges in the tournament. The [[adidas]] ball in use "really zipped through the air", which encouraged long-range shots at the high altitude.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=50}} In the first match, against [[South Korea national under-19 football team|South Korea]],<ref name="Korea">{{Cite web | url = http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=104/edition=191120/matches/match=30716/report.html| publisher = [[FIFA|F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de Football Association]] | title = FIFA World Youth Championship Mexico 1983: Korea Republic <U+2013> Scotland| accessdate =22 June 2011}}</ref> an element of the 26,000 crowd "clearly didn't like us at all ... I got absolutely pelted with coins ... and rotten fruit".{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=50}} The final insult was when he was hit on the back of the neck by a rancid-smelling plastic bag containing rotten fish.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=50}}  Gunn found it "intimidation ... a nightmare" but adopted the strategy of patrolling the edge of his area to stay out of range and had "one of the best games of my life":{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=50}} he kept a clean sheet as Scotland won 2<U+2013>0.<ref name="Korea"/> Scotland's coach and future manager of the full international team [[Andy Roxburgh]] told Gunn "it was the best performance he'd ever seen from a Scottish goalkeeper, at any level."{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=50}} The final group match, which Scotland needed to win in order to progress, was against the home side, [[Mexico national under-19 football team|Mexico]].{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=51}} The official attendance at the [[Azteca Stadium]] was 86,582,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=104/edition=191120/matches/match=30731/report.html| publisher = [[FIFA|F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de Football Association]] | title = FIFA World Youth Championship Mexico 1983: Mexico <U+2013> Scotland| accessdate =22 June 2011}}</ref> although Gunn believes the true figure was over 100,000.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=51}} Once more, Gunn was targeted with a variety of missiles, including a bottle of [[Johnnie Walker]], but as Scotland held on to their early 1<U+2013>0 lead, the fans became disillusioned with their own team and switched to sending a "hail of bottles and coins" on the Mexican players.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=51}} Scotland lost 1<U+2013>0 in the quarter final against [[Poland national under-19 football team|Poland]].{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=51}}

Gunn made six full international appearances for Scotland, conceding 10 goals.<ref name="scotland">{{cite web | url = http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=823&playerID=8&squadID=1 | title = Bryan Gunn | publisher = [[Scottish Football Association]] | accessdate=9 March 2011}}</ref> He was a member of the squad for the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]], but played in none of Scotland's three matches at the tournament,<ref name="scotland" /> as he was third-choice goalkeeper behind Jim Leighton and [[Andy Goram]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rsssf.com/tables/90full.html#sco | publisher = [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] | title = World Cup 1990 finals|accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> He made his Scotland debut in a pre-tournament [[friendly match]] against [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]], but was at fault for two Egyptian goals, resulting in a 3<U+2013>1 defeat for Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/article877893.ece|title=Scottish Diary: The top 10 Scottish goalkeeping gaffes|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|accessdate=9 March 2011|last=Baillie|first=Andrew|date=4 May 2003|location=London}}</ref> The embarrassment was made worse by the fact that his parents were watching.<ref name="author">{{Cite news | url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/author-of-a-different-kind-of-football-book-fighting-back-with-the-gunns-421437.html |work = [[The Independent]] | location=London|title = Author of a different kind of football book: Fighting back with the Gunns | first = Phil| last = Shaw| date =25 October 2006 | accessdate =13 May 2011}}</ref> Gunn made four appearances for Scotland in [[1994 FIFA World Cup qualification]] matches.<ref name="scotland" /> His last [[Cap (sport)|cap]] was as a second-half substitute in a 3<U+2013>1 friendly defeat by the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] in May 1994.<ref name="scotland" />

===Honours===

* [[UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship|UEFA European Under-18 Football Championship]] winner, 1982<ref name="u19 champion" />
* [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]] winner, [[1983 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1983]]<ref name="ecwc">{{Cite news | url = http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/sport/1983-heroes-and-current-European.4282102.jp | work = [[The Scotsman]] | location=Edinburgh| accessdate =23 March 2011| date = 12 July 2008 | first= Scott |last=Coull| title = 1983 heroes and current European champions on show in glamour friendly}}</ref>
* [[Scottish League Cup]] winner, [[1985 Scottish League Cup Final|1985]]{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=60}}
* [[Norwich City player of the year]] ([[Barry Butler (footballer born 1934)|Barry Butler]] trophy) winner, 1988, 1993<ref name="poty" />
* [[Norwich City F.C. Hall of Fame]] inaugural member, 2002<ref name="hof">{{cite web | url = http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/History/0,,10355~1840305,00.html | title = New Hall of Fame members enrolled | publisher = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City F.C]] | accessdate =9 March 2011 | date = 28 February 2011|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120426052031/http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/History/0,,10355~1840305,00.html|archivedate=26 April 2012}}</ref>

==Coaching career and other activities==
Gunn obtained his [[UEFA Pro Licence|coaching certification]] while still with Aberdeen, in 1983, at [[Largs]].<ref name="square">{{cite web| url = http://articles.squarefootball.net/squarefootball/2006/09/3679-exclusive.html| title=3679: Exclusive Interview: Bryan Gun | first=Colin|last=Illingworth|publisher=squarefootball.net | accessdate=22 March 2011l}}</ref> After his retirement from playing professional football in 1999,<ref name="bbcnorfolk" /> Gunn initially worked on the hospitality staff at Carrow Road, particularly in "The Gunn Club", a catering outlet named in his honour.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/2003/01/21/delia-quits-cooking-for-canaries-91466-12554137/ |title=Delia quits cooking for Canaries|first=Catherine|last=Jones|work=[[Western Mail (Wales)]]|accessdate=10 February 2013|date=21 January 2003|location=Cardiff}}</ref>

Over the years, Gunn progressed from hospitality into other corporate positions at Norwich; he acted as sponsorship manager from 1999 to 2006.<ref name="square2">{{cite web | url = http://articles.squarefootball.net/squarefootball/2006/09/3680-long-long.html|publisher = squarefootball.net| title =3680: Long, Long Distance Goals | accessdate =22 March 2011| first = Hugh|last=Larkin|date=25 September 2006}}</ref> Manager [[Peter Grant (footballer)|Peter Grant]] moved Gunn to the "backroom" sports management side of the business in 2007.<ref name="liaison">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/n/norwich/6342553.stm | title=Grant adds to backroom staff|publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 February 2007|accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> Gunn worked in a liaison role in negotiations of possible transfers and loan signings, tasks where he could make use of contacts gained during his playing career.<ref name="liaison" />

When [[Glenn Roeder]] was appointed manager in November 2007, goalkeeping coach James Hollman parted company with the club, and Gunn replaced him for the rest of the season<U+2014>his first formal coaching role.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2301454/Norwich-appoint-Bryan-Gunn-to-unearth-gems.html | work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] | title = Norwich appoint Bryan Gunn to unearth gems | date = 24 May 2008 | first = Rick |last=Waghorn|accessdate=10 March 2011 | location=London}}</ref> Later in the season, Gunn was promoted to head of player recruitment, while retaining his goalkeeping coach role.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/n/norwich/7417420.stm| title = Gunn gets new role at Canaries | date = 23 May 2008| accessdate=9 March 2011|publisher = BBC Sport}}</ref>

===Manager of Norwich City===
Following the sacking of Roeder as Norwich manager in January 2009, Gunn was asked to take temporary charge of the first team.<ref name="Gunn to take charge of Barnsley clash">{{cite news | title=Gunn to take charge of Barnsley clash | publisher=[[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City F.C]] | date=16 January 2009 | url=http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/NewsDetails/0,,10355~1521521,00.html | accessdate=21 January 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120315233347/http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/NewsDetails/0,,10355~1521521,00.html|archivedate=15 March 2012}}</ref> In an interview with [[BBC Radio Norfolk]], he revealed that he "told the players that they've let people down."<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/n/norwich/7832734.stm| title = Gunn named Norwich caretaker boss | publisher = BBC Sport | date= 16 January 2009 | accessdate =9 March 2011}}</ref> In his first match as caretaker manager, he received "a euphoric reception" from the fans,<ref name="sos" /> and Norwich beat [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] 4<U+2013>0.<ref name="Norwich 4-0 Barnsley">{{cite news | title=Norwich 4<U+2013>0 Barnsley | publisher=BBC Sport | date=17 January 2009 | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_1/7815952.stm | accessdate=21 January 2009}}</ref> The players were equally supportive: according to ''[[Scotland on Sunday]]'', "in the dressing room afterwards, [Norwich] midfielder, [[Darel Russell]], dragged the chairman, [[Roger Munby]], into the shower, and demanded that Gunn be appointed permanently."<ref name="sos" /> Momentum gathered, and a [[Facebook]] group called "Bryan Gunn for manager", created by his then 17-year-old daughter, Melissa, soon attracted about 3,000 members.<ref name="sos" /> Gunn considered applying for the role on a longer-term basis; he had previously applied without success to be Norwich manager in 1998. On 19 January 2009 he phoned the directors and requested to be considered.<ref name="sos" /> He was interviewed that afternoon and "by 10.30 am the next day had been appointed manager until the end of the season".<ref name="sos" /><ref name="Gunn named new Norwich boss">{{cite news | title=Gunn named new Norwich boss | publisher=[[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City F.C]] | date=21 January 2009 | url=http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/NewsDetails/0,,10355~1527367,00.html | accessdate=21 January 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120315233406/http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/NewsDetails/0,,10355~1527367,00.html|archivedate=15 March 2012}}</ref>

Gunn appointed a backroom staff of former Norwich colleagues, making [[Ian Crook]] first-team coach and [[John Deehan]] chief [[scout (sport)|scout]].<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.edp24.co.uk/sport/norwich-city-fc/gunn_named_as_norwich_city_boss_1_644302 | title = Gunn named as Norwich City boss| work = [[Eastern Daily Press]] | location=Norfolk| accessdate =10 February 2013| date = 21 January 2009}}</ref> However, the initial turnaround in form could not be maintained; having lost their last three games of the season, Norwich were relegated from the [[Football League Championship|Championship]].<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_1/8015098.stm | title = Norwich drop down to League One| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 3 May 2009| accessdate =9 March 2011}}</ref> Gunn labelled his players as an "embarrassment" after the 4<U+2013>2 defeat to [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] that sealed relegation to [[Football League One|League One]].<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2009/may/03/charlton-athletic-norwich-city-championship-relegation | work = [[The Guardian]] | title = Inept Norwich confirm their own relegation doom before half-time | first = Sachin|last=Nakrani| accessdate =29 March 2011 | date = 3 May 2009 | location=London}}</ref> Despite relegation to the third tier of English football for the first time in nearly 50 years,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/UK-News/Norwich-City-Relegated-To-League-One-Of-English-Football-For-The-First-Time-In-Half-A-Century/Article/200905115274350 | title = Norwich City Relegated In Good Company | first = Rob | last=Kirk| accessdate=24 March 2011| date = 4 May 2009| publisher = [[Sky News]]}}</ref> Norwich re-appointed Gunn as manager for the 2009<U+2013>10 season.<ref name="sky">{{Cite news | url = http://sport.scotsman.com/football/Norwich-opt-for-Gunn-.5265177.jp | title = Norwich opt for Gunn as their No1 | work =[[The Scotsman]]|location=Edinburgh | date= 14 May 2009|accessdate =8 March 2011}}</ref> Crook, as first team coach, and former Canary [[Ian Butterworth]], as assistant manager,<ref name="sky" /> completed the management team.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1057245.html | publisher = [[FIFA]] | accessdate =23 March 2011| date = 13 May 2009 | title = Norwich keep faith with Gunn}}</ref> Over the summer, Gunn signed 12 players,<ref name="terminate">{{cite web | url = http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/NewsDetails/0,,10355~1755120,00.html| publisher = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City F.C]] | title = Gunn's contract terminated | accessdate =4 March 2011|date=17 August 2009|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090817124628/http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/NewsDetails/0,,10355~1755120,00.html|archivedate=17 August 2009}}</ref> most of those on free transfers,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/sport/football/2577215/League-One-preview.html | work=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] | location=London| title=League One preview | date=7 August 2009}}</ref> including Australian [[Michael Theoklitos]], a goalkeeper from [[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/NewsDetails/0,,10355~1716687,00.html | title = Aussie keeper joins Canaries| accessdate =24 March 2011| date = 8 July 2009| publisher = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City F.C]]|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120302072430/http://www.canaries.co.uk/page/NewsDetails/0,,10355~1716687,00.html|archivedate=2 March 2012}}</ref> He then steered the club through a programme of pre-season friendly matches, in which Norwich was unbeaten.<ref name="terminate" />

Just under a month after Gunn's reappointment, Norwich appointed a new managing director, [[David McNally (football)|David McNally]].<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/n/norwich/8097050.stm | publisher = BBC Sport| title = McNally appointed Canaries chief |accessdate =24 March 2011| date = 12 June 2009}}</ref> With the disappointment of relegation, Gunn's reappointment was controversial,<ref name="daily mail fired">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1206601/Gunn-fired-Norwich-City-legend-Bryan-axed-just-seven-days-new-season.html |title=Gunn fired! Norwich City legend Bryan axed just a week into the new season|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=14 August 2009|accessdate=29 March 2011|first=Ashley|last=Gray |location=London}}</ref> and more was to follow. For the opening game of the new season, Norwich were to play at home against [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]], rivals for the [[Pride of Anglia]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.cu-fc.com/page/News/0,,10424~1027289,00.html| title = U's Gain Anglia Acclaim | date = 18 May 2007 | accessdate =13 May 2011| publisher = [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United F.C]]|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110807180855/http://www.cu-fc.com/page/News/0,,10424~1027289,00.html|archivedate=7 August 2011}}</ref> Gunn's team suffered a 7<U+2013>1 defeat,<ref name="megadefeat">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_2/8186227.stm | title = Norwich 1<U+2013>7 Colchester | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 8 August 2009 | accessdate =8 August 2009}}</ref> and Theoklitos, signed by Gunn on a free transfer,<ref name="blunders">{{Cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/n/norwich/8193128.stm | title = Norwich keeper admits to blunders | date = 10 August 2009| accessdate =24 March 2011| publisher = BBC Sport}}</ref> was particularly blamed by the press for the scale of the defeat.<ref name="megadefeat" /> Theoklitos later admitted it was "the worst performance of my career".<ref name="blunders" /> Despite this, he retained Gunn's support,<ref name="blunders" /> although in the eventuality, Theoklitos never played for Norwich again.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/n/norwich/8552313.stm | title = Goalkeeper Michael Theoklitos leaves Norwich City | publisher = BBC Sport| accessdate =24 March 2011| date = 5 March 2010}}</ref>

As early as during the match itself, fans and the media began to react strongly to the shock of Norwich's worst-ever home defeat. During the first half, after the side had gone 4<U+2013>0 down, two supporters approached the Norwich bench, appearing to throw their season tickets at Gunn.<ref name="megadefeat" /> Many fans walked out before the match ended, and around 300 people protested outside the ground afterwards.<ref name="daily mail fired" /> Media coverage of the match was unsurprisingly negative: the BBC used terms such as "calamitous defending", "Colchester run riot", "dismal", and a "disastrous start";<ref name="terminate" /> journalists also speculated about Gunn's competence as a manager.<ref name="terminate" /> Matters seemed to stabilise a little with a 4<U+2013>0 [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] win at [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil]] the following Tuesday.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/league_cup/8190090.stm | title = Yeovil 0<U+2013>4 Norwich| publisher = BBC Sport | accessdate =13 May 2011|date = 11 August 2009}}</ref> However, Gunn was sacked by McNally on 14 August 2009, six days after the defeat by Colchester.<ref name="megadefeat" />

Gunn was influenced in his management philosophy by former Norwich manager [[Mike Walker (Welsh footballer)|Mike Walker]].<ref name="sos" /> Himself a former goalkeeper, Walker believed<U+2014>contrary to popular opinion<U+2014>that goalkeepers can make good managers because their excellent view of the game enables them to develop a good tactical awareness.<ref name="sos" /> Gunn's short time at Norwich remains his only experience of professional football management and he has subsequently moved into a business career.<ref name="sbase" />

===Managerial statistics===
