==After football==
Gunn began work in November 2009 as director of business development for OneStream, part of the Digital Phone Company,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.onestreamhosting.co.uk/press/2010/03/bryan-gunn-and-great-yarmouth-based-onestream-raise-over-1500-for-big-c-cancer-charity-by-not-shaving/ | title = Bryan Gunn and Great Yarmouth based OneStream raise over <U+00A3>1500 for Big C Cancer Charity by not shaving! | accessdate =11 May 2011 | publisher = OneStream}}</ref> based in [[Great Yarmouth]].<ref name="One">{{cite web | url = http://www.onestream.co.uk/bryangunn/| publisher = OneStream| date= 9 November 2009 | title = Bryan Gunn joins OneStream|accessdate=24 May 2011}}</ref> His role was to "promote their communication and mobile working solutions".<ref name="One" />

In 2011, Gunn announced he was leaving OneStream for a new job as a sports agent.<ref name="agent">{{Cite news | url = http://www.edp24.co.uk/news/canaries_legend_gunn_to_leave_norfolk_1_893364 | title = Canaries legend Gunn to leave Norfolk| first = Kim| last = Briscoe| work = [[Eastern Daily Press]]| accessdate =23 May 2011| location= Norfolk| date = 14 May 2011}}</ref> In his new role as director of talent recruitment at a sports agency, he is responsible for recruiting young footballers.<ref name="agent" />

==Family and personal life==
Gunn's wife, [[Susan Gunn|Susan]], is a painter. She won the inaugural [[Sovereign Art Prize]] in 2008, which included a cash award of <U+20AC>25,000.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4612086.stm
|title=Painter scoops 25,000 euros prize
|publisher=BBC News
|date=14 January 2006
|accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> According to ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', before her marriage, Susan was "a beauty queen turned lingerie model" who "launched a fashion business".<ref name="Susan">{{Cite news | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1509763/Footballers-wife-paints-a-different-picture-to-make-a-mark.html|title = Footballer's wife paints a different picture to make a mark | work = [[The Daily Telegraph]]| accessdate =9 March 2011| date = 6 February 2006 | first = Roya|last=Nikkhah | location=London}}</ref> The couple met in Spain, where Susan had a bridal wear company,<ref name="Susan" /> when Gunn was there on holiday.<ref name="author" /> She told the ''Telegraph'', "When I first met Bryan, I knew nothing about football and had no idea who he was because he told me he was a [[joiner]]."<ref name="Susan" />
Gunn explained that he was unsure what her attitude would be to footballers;{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=101}} he later confessed his calling to her. He proposed within three days of their meeting,<ref name="Susan" /> and they were married the following year.<ref name="Susan" /> They lived in [[Framingham Pigot]], near Norwich, until moving to [[Cheshire]] in May 2011.<ref name="agent" /> The Gunns have had three children: Francesca, Melissa and Angus.<ref name="Susan" /> Melissa is a model,<ref name="sos" /> while their son, Angus, is a footballer and plays in goal, like his father.<ref name="Angus">{{Cite news | url = http://www.edp24.co.uk/sport/norwich-city-fc/norwich_city_s_gunn_gets_chance_to_shine_for_england_1_675710| work = [[Eastern Daily Press]] | location = Norfolk | accessdate =8 March 2011 | date = 7 October 2010|title = Norwich City<U+2019>s Gunn gets chance to shine for England | first = David |last=Cuffley}}</ref> On the books as a youth player at Norwich City, in October 2010 he was selected for [[England national under-16 football team|England under-16s]], a full year ahead of the age group.<ref name="Angus" /><ref>{{cite news|last=McCarthy|first=David|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/youth-football/2011/03/29/ex-scotland-keeper-bryan-gunn-s-son-set-to-keep-goal-for-england-against-scots-86908-23023524/|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]] | location=Glasgow|accessdate=30 March 2011|date=29 March 2011|title = Victory Shield: Ex-Scotland keeper Bryan Gunn's son set to keep goal <U+2013> for England against Scots}}</ref>

According to ''[[Scotland on Sunday]]'', Gunn suffers from [[ankylosing spondylitis]], "a rheumatic spinal condition", diagnosed in about 1995, "which he controls with medication".<ref name="sos" /> He appeared in an [[ITV2]] celebrity football quiz called "Taking the Pitch" in 1998, alongside singer [[Fish (singer)|Fish]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.the-company.com/email/e1998-11-04.htm| title = Subject: Fish 98 <U+2013> Setlists, American CD's, VH1 and other stories | publisher = the-company.com | accessdate =11 May 2011 | date = 4 November 1998}}</ref> Gunn's autobiography<U+2014>''In Where it Hurts''<U+2014>was published in 2006, and includes a foreword by his former manager Alex Ferguson.<ref name="author" /> He said of writing the book, "it brought up a lot of good memories and a lot of awkward memories".<ref name="Aberdeen" /> The book was described by ''[[The Times]]'' as "shot through with sharp humour and astute observation".<ref name="author" /> The publishers agreed to donate <U+00A3>1 to Gunn's Leukaemia appeal fund for every book sold.<ref name="square2" />

===Leukaemia appeal===
In 1992, Gunn's two-year-old daughter, Francesca, was diagnosed with [[leukaemia]].<ref name="fixed" /> Norwich City fans were at first astonished by the sight of the goalkeeper running out with a completely shaven head.{{sfn|Baldwin|1993|p=102}} In the words of author and Norwich supporter, Kevin Baldwin, "Occasionally, the gap between the crowd and the players can cause unfortunate misunderstandings. A few months ago, Gunn shaved his head and we all laughed at him ... I was especially keen ... to shout "Baldy!" ... It now turns out that his daughter was undergoing chemotherapy at the time, which made her hair fall out. He shaved his head to show her that this was nothing to be ashamed of. Sorry, Bryan."{{sfn|Baldwin|1993|p=102}} When news spread of the reason for Gunn's shaven head, he received "support from the whole of the sporting world and the people of Norfolk".<ref name="Giving">{{cite web | url = http://www.charitygiving.co.uk/minisites/default.asp?subname=bryangunn | title = Bryan Gunn's appeal home page | publisher = Charity Giving| accessdate =8 March 2011}}</ref>

Gunn describes the period of Francesca's illness and death and how it caused him to reflect on his career:
<blockquote>"We had a charmed life ... then Francesca became ill. There was a game in the autumn of '92 ... that we lost 7<U+2013>1 at Blackburn. The team stayed in a bleak hotel and it rained endlessly. I just wanted to get back home. With hindsight you think, 'Why the bloody hell was I playing?' Very soon afterwards, Francesca died. She was sleeping between us. I realised what was happening and woke Susan. We cradled Francesca and cried."<ref name="author" /></blockquote>

Francesca died in 1992, aged two.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/edinburgh/ExHibs-keepers-cancer-charity-comes.2778391.jp |title=Ex-Hibs keeper's cancer charity comes to Capital |date=25 May 2006 |accessdate=8 March 2011 |work=[[Edinburgh Evening News]]|location=Edinburgh}}</ref> Gunn played a match for Norwich against [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] at Carrow Road just days after his daughter died; he said of it, "When I ran out, I thought, wow, I could feel the whole stadium was with me. I never thought about packing it in."<ref name="fixed" /> At the end of the season, Gunn won [[Norwich City player of the year|Norwich's player of the year award]],<ref name="bbcnorfolk">{{cite web | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/norfolk/content/articles/2009/01/19/brian_gunn_20090119_feature.shtml | title = Gunning his way to success | publisher = BBC Norfolk | accessdate =9 March 2011 | date = 21 January 2009}}</ref> as the club finished third in the Premiership, its highest ever league position.<ref name="bbcnorfolk" />

Following Francesca's death, Gunn established "Bryan Gunn's Leukaemia Appeal", a fund to raise money to combat the disease. He initially set a target of <U+00A3>10,000,<ref name="fixed" /> but by 2011 he has raised <U+00A3>1,000,000,<ref>{{cite web |url =http://www.bryangunnsappeal.org/| title = Bryan Gunn's Appeal | publisher=bryangunnsappeal.org|accessdate=10 March 2011}}</ref> under the auspices of [[The Dove Trust]].<ref name="gaps">{{Cite news | url = http://www.edp24.co.uk/news/gunn_cancer_helpline_goes_nationwide_1_538453 | title = Gunn cancer helpline goes nationwide| first=Mark | last=Nicholls| work = [[Eastern Daily Press]] | location=Norfolk| accessdate =10 March 2011| date = 2 January 2006}}</ref> The fund aims to address three issues:
<blockquote>
"Equipping local hospitals to be better able to deal with children suffering from the disease on both in-patient and out-patient bases. Providing training for nurses and other staff involved in the care of children with leukaemia over and above that which is available from their employers. To support<!-- sic --> further research into the causes and cures of leukaemia."<ref name="Giving" /></blockquote>

The third of these ambitions has prompted the funding of research into leukaemia at the Norwich-based [[University of East Anglia]]. Gunn says:
<blockquote>"The ultimate aim is to find a cure and if that can be done in the laboratory at the University of East Anglia bearing Francesca's name, then it would be the biggest testimony of all. Norwich is now one of the leading centres for leukaemia research and, with links to computer systems around the world, hopefully we'll get there."<ref name="fixed" /></blockquote>

In addition to the research, Gunn set up a telephone support line that offers advice and assistance for parents of children who have leukaemia or other forms of cancer.<ref name="gaps" /> Known as gaps:line (an [[acronym]] for Gunn Appeal Parent Support), the service quickly grew. From its initial pilot launch in Norfolk in early 2004, it expanded to cover the "eastern region" by the end of the year, and launched nationally in early 2006.<ref name="gaps" /> The appeal has also funded other research and support work.<ref name="Giving" />

==Playing style, personality, achievements and legacy==
As a player, Gunn was described as a "a leader with a big presence" by his manager at Hibernian, Alex McLeish.<ref name="highbeam" /> Aberdeen manager Alex Ferguson recalls, "the first thing that hit me was his personality. It was abundantly clear ... that he was a warm, outgoing and endearing character",{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=xiii}} adding "He was a tremendous young keeper... always totally professional and I could never fault his discipline, effort or commitment."{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=xiv}}

Gunn had a "fantastic rapport with the Norwich supporters".{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=74}} As a player, he liked "to tease the crowd during the game".{{sfn|Baldwin|1993|p=101}} Before each half of a match, Gunn would run toward his goal and pretend to attempt to [[head-butt]] the [[Goal (sport)#Association football|crossbar]].{{sfn|Baldwin|1993|p=101}} Gunn says this is a habit he began as a youngster,{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=73}} and cannot remember how or why he began to do it.{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=74}} Norwich fans noticed it soon after his arrival at the club and, in Gunn's words, "would wait until I got to about the 18-yard line and then start a small "Wooo..." which would build into a full-blown "WOOOO ... AH!" ... I loved it and came close to smacking my head against the woodwork a couple of times".{{sfn|Gunn|Piper|2006|p=74}} <!-- Gunn did actually make contact with the bar before a match against xxxx in xxxx, and played the game despite some symptoms of concussion.{{Citation needed|date=May 2012}} --> During play, he would cup his ear, which would prompt shouts of "Bryan, Bryan, give us a wave".{{sfn|Baldwin|1993|p=101}}

Gunn is described as "a legend in Norwich",<ref name="sos">{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Paul|url=http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/sport/Interview-Gunn-slings-his-hat.4910961.jp|work=[[Scotland on Sunday]]|location=Edinburgh| publisher=|date=25 January 2009|accessdate=15 March 2011|title=Interview: Gunn slings his hat in the ring at City}}</ref> the result of his long years of service as player and official for the club.<ref name="sos" /> In 2002, he was made one of 25 inaugural members of the [[Norwich City F.C. Hall of Fame|Norwich City Hall of Fame]].<ref name="hof" /> A 2005 ''[[Football Focus]]'' fan poll for "Norwich's cult heroes" saw Gunn finish in first place.<ref name="poll">{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/football_focus/4226639.stm
|title=Norwich's cult heroes
|publisher=BBC Sport
|date=4 February 2005
|accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> He polled 37% of votes, ahead of [[Robert Fleck]] and [[Iwan Roberts]].<ref name="poll" /> Gunn is one of just nine players to have twice won [[Norwich City player of the year]], in 1988 and 1993, and the only goalkeeper to do so. In 2003, as part of the [[Premier League 10 Seasons Awards]], he was one of 10 players to be recognised by the [[Premier League]] with an "Outstanding Contribution to the Community" award.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/charlton_athletic/2784991.stm |title=Powell in line for award |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 February 2003 |accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> In response to his achievements with Norwich City and his charitable work, which has benefited the local university, in 2002 Gunn was made [[List of Shrievalties|Sheriff of Norwich]] for the year by the City Council.<ref name="gaps" />

